This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely disseminated, but also provides more details than the fossils, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
. According to what scientists say, the plumage of this animal was brownish-red in the upper part, with a pale or carotene-like coloration in the lower part.
The discovery also allows you to obtain detailed information about the evolution of the feathers of birds.
Because the plumage of the dinosaur is not equipped with the basic structure, the so-called rachis, but has instead other characteristics typical of feathers, barbs and barbules, the researchers have concluded that the rachis is probably the result of an evolutionary development subsequent to such characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that it was not used for flight, but rather for thermoregulation or courtship. The researchers hypothesize that, although it is the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, the specimen shows adult plumage and not juvenile plumage.
